# /incidents â†’ status site. The explorer doesn't have an
# /incidents listing page; per-incident postmortems live on
# status.ratesengine.net under /incident/[slug]/. The status
# site IS the incidents listing â€” bounce both /incidents and
# bare /incident/<slug> to the right host so a typed URL or an
# external share lands on the canonical page rather than the
# explorer's catch-all 404. Found via 404-audit 2026-05-10.
/incidents           https://status.ratesengine.net/             301
/incidents/          https://status.ratesengine.net/             301
/incident/*          https://status.ratesengine.net/incident/:splat  301

# /converter â†’ /convert/USD/XLM/. "Converter" (with the -er
# suffix) is what users type from muscle memory (xe.com,
# coinbase.com/converter, etc.). The actual route is /convert,
# parameterised by [from]/[to]. Pre-redirect to a sensible default
# pair so a typed URL lands on a working page instead of the 404.
/converter           /convert/USD/XLM/   301
/converter/          /convert/USD/XLM/   301
/convert             /convert/USD/XLM/   301
/convert/            /convert/USD/XLM/   301

# /oracles/<name> â†’ /oracles/. Per-oracle detail pages don't
# exist yet (only the listing); a typed `/oracles/reflector` or
# `/oracles/band` would 404. Bounce to the listing rather than
# the catch-all 404 â€” the listing already has each oracle's
# methodology + last-update inline.
/oracles/*           /oracles/    301

# Common-name 404s â€” natural URL guesses that should land on the
# canonical category page rather than the 404 catch-all. Each was
# returning 404 in the audit on 2026-05-10. The /coins â†’ /assets
# rules exist higher in this file already; this block adds the
# adjacent singular/synonym variants so a user typing /pool, /pools,
# /token, /tokens, /coin, /price, /prices in the address bar lands
# somewhere useful instead of hitting the static-export 404.
/pool          /dexes/                            301
/pool/         /dexes/                            301
/pools         /dexes/                            301
/pools/        /dexes/                            301
/coin          /assets/                           301
/coin/         /assets/                           301
/token         /assets/                           301
/token/        /assets/                           301
/tokens        /assets/                           301
/tokens/       /assets/                           301
/price         /markets/                          301
/price/        /markets/                          301
/prices        /markets/                          301
/prices/       /markets/                          301
# /api existed without trailing slash via the cross-host rule above;
# add the trailing-slash variant so /api/ â†’ api.ratesengine.net too.
/api/          https://api.ratesengine.net/       301
# /docs and /docs/* â€” the rendered API reference lives at
# docs.ratesengine.net (splat preserves the deep-link path so
# /docs/v1/price â†’ docs.ratesengine.net/v1/price).
/docs          https://docs.ratesengine.net/      301
/docs/         https://docs.ratesengine.net/      301
/docs/*        https://docs.ratesengine.net/:splat 301

# /favicon.ico â†’ /icon.svg. Next 15's `src/app/icon.svg` metadata
# route serves the SVG and emits the right <link rel="icon"> in the
# rendered HTML, so modern browsers find the favicon via that link
# tag and never ask for /favicon.ico. But many crawlers, RSS
# readers, link-preview cards, and browser address-bar fallbacks
# STILL hit /favicon.ico unconditionally â€” without this rule every
# one of those requests was a noisy 404. SVG favicons render in
# Chrome 80+, Firefox 80+, Safari 15+, Edge â€” essentially every
# client shipping for 4+ years. Older clients that wouldn't render
# the SVG would have rendered nothing here anyway (no prior .ico),
# so this is strictly an improvement.
/favicon.ico             /icon.svg   301
